                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d929">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2481: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-26T12:00:00+09:00"
                            >April 26, 1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 3:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your [<hi rend="italic">Chungking’s</hi>] April 25, 11 a.m.<note n="9"
                        xml:id="d929fn1">See footnote 8, <ref target="#pg_859">p. 859</ref>.</note>
                    I have notified Senior Consul today in writing that the Government of the United
                    States consents to the establishment of the provisional council under the terms
                    of resolution number 4. Several other governments, including the British,
                    Japanese and German, have also communicated their consent.</p>
                <p>Sent to Chungking. Repeated to the Department and Peiping. Code text by air mail
                    to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
